Git Local To Remote Guide
Git Step-by-Step Documentation: Local to Remote
1. Create a Local Project

Open PowerShell or terminal.

Create a new project folder:

mkdir MyNewProject
cd MyNewProject

Create a README file:

echo "# My New Project" > README.md

Initialize Git:

git init

Check status:

git status
2. Configure Git User

Set your Git identity:

git config user.name "Arun Vangala"
git config user.email "vangalaarun74@gmail.com"

Verify:

git config --list
3. Stage and Commit Changes

Stage all files:

git add .

Commit your changes:

git commit -m "Initial commit with README"

Check commit status:

git status
4. Create Remote Repository on GitHub

Go to GitHub → New Repository

Repository name: MyNewProject

Do NOT check “Add README”

Click Create repository

5. Connect Local Repo to GitHub

Copy the HTTPS URL of your GitHub repo:

https://github.com/ArunVangala/MyNewProject.git

Add remote:

git remote add origin https://github.com/ArunVangala/MyNewProject.git

Verify:

git remote -v
6. Push Local Project to GitHub

Rename branch to main:

git branch -M main

Push to remote:

git push -u origin main

Verify on GitHub: All files should appear.

7. Create and Work on Branches

Create a new branch:

git checkout -b feature-branch

Make changes, then stage & commit:

git add .
git commit -m "Add new feature"

Push branch to GitHub:

git push origin feature-branch

Merge branch into main:

git checkout main
git merge feature-branch

Delete branch (optional):

git branch -d feature-branch
8. Daily Workflow

Pull latest changes:

git pull origin main

Make changes, stage, commit, and push:

git add .
git commit -m "Your message"
git push
Tips

Always work on a branch for features or bug fixes.

Commit often with descriptive messages.

Use git status to check repository state before committing.

Use Personal Access Token (PAT) for HTTPS push authentication.
